# Python Module Privacy

Leading underscore = private to the module. No underscore = public API.

## Rule

- Private names (`_hash_code`, `_CODE_ALPHABET`, `_MyHelper`) **may be
  renamed, deleted, or resignatured at any time**. Never import them
  from another module — that includes both `from app.x import _y`
  and `from .x import _y`.
- Public names are contracts. Changing them is a breaking change for
  every other module in the codebase.
- Default new helpers to private. Promote to public only when a
  second module needs them — and pick a public name at that moment
  (rename to drop the underscore, document the new contract).
- If you find yourself wanting to import `_foo` from elsewhere, ask
  the owning module to expose a public function (or move `_foo` into
  a shared helper module) instead of reaching across the privacy
  boundary.

Same rule for class attributes: `self._cache` is internal,
`self.user_id` is part of the contract. Don't use double-leading
underscore at module level — that's class-scope name mangling, a
different feature.

## Why

The convention is already idiomatic Python, but it's been
informal in this repo. Codifying + enforcing it stops the slow
drift where a `_helper` in one module gets imported by three
others, then can't be renamed without a multi-PR sweep. It also
gives reviewers a single sentence to point at when they want a
helper kept private.

## Enforcement

The rule is reviewed manually for now. Ruff's `PLC2701`
(`Private name import ...`) is the mechanical gate; it lives in
the Pylint preview catalogue and would catch every cross-module
`from x import _y`. We haven't enabled it yet because the existing
codebase has ~124 violations (mostly tests reaching into module-
local helpers) — a focused sweep PR will land that work before
flipping the switch. The rule's `select` opt-in is documented in
`backend/pyproject.toml` so the next pass knows where to land.

## Verify

"Am I about to import a name starting with `_` from another module?
If so: should I promote that name to public on the owning module,
or move it to a shared helper, instead of reaching past the privacy
boundary?"

## Patterns

Bad — reaches into another module's private surface:

```python
# Module B
from app.crud.conversation import _normalize_title  # ❌
```

Good — owning module exposes a public name:

```python
# Module A (app/crud/conversation.py)
def normalize_title(title: str) -> str:
    ...

# Module B
from app.crud.conversation import normalize_title  # ✅
```

Good — shared helper module for cross-cutting concerns:

```python
# app/core/text.py — shared, public-by-convention
def normalize_title(title: str) -> str: ...

# Both crud/conversation.py and crud/message.py:
from app.core.text import normalize_title
```
